## Debugging Benefits

Well-named IDs make debugging significantly easier:

### Browser DevTools

```html
<!-- Bad: Difficult to identify -->
<div id="d1">
  <button id="b1" onclick="fn1()">Click</button>
</div>

<!-- DevTools shows: "div#d1", "button#b1" -->
<!-- No context about purpose -->

<!-- Good: Self-documenting -->
<div id="user-profile-container">
  <button id="user-settings-save-button" data-action="click->profile#save">
    Save Settings
  </button>
</div>

<!-- DevTools shows: "div#user-profile-container", "button#user-settings-save-button" -->
<!-- Immediately clear what each element is for -->
```

### Console Selection

```javascript
// Easy element selection
const button = document.getElementById('user-settings-save-button');
const form = document.getElementById('article-edit-form');
const input = document.getElementById('user-email-input');

// Clear what you're selecting
console.log(button); // "button#user-settings-save-button"
```

### Error Messages

```javascript
// Bad ID in error
"Cannot find element with ID 'btn1'"
// What is btn1? Where is it? What does it do?

// Good ID in error
"Cannot find element with ID 'user-login-submit-button'"
// Ah, it's the login form submit button
```

### Testing

```ruby
# System tests with clear selectors
assert_selector "button#user-login-submit-button"
fill_in "user-email-input", with: "test@example.com"
click_button "user-login-submit-button"

# Immediately clear what test is doing
```

